<li>[ 20 ] Outten , F.W. , Outten , C.E. , Hale , J. and O'Halloran , T.V. ( 2000 ) Transcriptional activation of an Escherichia coli copper e ¥ ux regulon by the chromosomal MerR homologue , CueR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12829264" target="_blank">12829264</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>CueR binding occurs in vitro in both the presence and the absence of RNA polymerase with or without copper ions present but , in the presence of CueR , RNA polymerase and copper ions , permanganatesensitive transcription complexes were formed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11136469" target="_blank">11136469</a>]<br></li>
<li>29 and 210 ) in the presence of RNA polymerase and CueR together , indicating a low level of transcription initiation , and this is increased considerably in the presence of copper or silver salts .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11136469" target="_blank">11136469</a>]<br></li>
<li>Similar to other MerR metalloregulatory family members , CueR exhibits a metal-selective behavior in vivo , activating the transcription of copA in response to elevated extracellular concentrations of the salts of coinage metals , such as copper , silver , and gold , but not of zinc and mercury ( 7 -- 9 , 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12958362" target="_blank">12958362</a>]<br></li>
<li>CueR activates expression of the copA promoter ( PcopA ) upon addition of copper or silver , but not nickel , lead , cadmium , mercury , or zinc salts ( 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446701" target="_blank">12446701</a>]<br></li>
<li>We show that CueR can also be activated by gold salts and that Cys112 and Cys120 are involved in recognition of gold , silver , and copper salts .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446701" target="_blank">12446701</a>]<br></li>
<li>Here we show that CueR activates the PcopA promoter in the presence of gold salts and that cysteine residues , equivalent to those in MerR , are required for activation by copper , silver , and gold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446701" target="_blank">12446701</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on the sequence similarities among CueR , ZntR , and MerR ( Fig. 6B ) , it is likely that CueR detects cytoplasmic copper stress and activates transcription in response to increasing copper concentrations .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10915804" target="_blank">10915804</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , CueR activates transcription of PcopA in response to gold ions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446701" target="_blank">12446701</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the case of copper-response systems , for instance , not only copper but also silver and gold are known to-bind to the C-terminus of CueR ( the sensor / regulator protein of the copper-response one-component system ) and stimulate transcription in vivo and in vitro of the CueR-dependent copA gene ( Stoyanov et al. , 2001 ; Stoyanov and Brown , 2003 ; Changela et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>While CopA , the principal copper ef ¯ ux ATPase , is regulated by the MerR homologue CueR , there exists also a two-component system ( CusS/R ) that activates transcription of its adjacent genes coding for a proton/cation antiporter complex ( Munson et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11243806" target="_blank">11243806</a>]<br></li>
<li>As in the case of MerR , the copper-bound CueR may induce a conformational change of the copA promoter in the CueRcopA promoter-RNA polymerase ternary complex so as to reduce the actual distance between -10 and -35 signals ( Outten et al. , 2000 ; Stoyanov et al. , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>Intracellular copper levels are controlled by a pair of transcriptional-regulators , CueR ( Outten et al. , 2000 ; Petersen and Moller , 2000 ) and CusR ( Munson et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16956381" target="_blank">16956381</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast to the CueR regulator which responds to cytoplasmic copper , the CusRS system responds to periplasmic copper levels ( Outten et al. 2001 ; Munson et al. 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>This important pump is induced by copper via the action of CueR , a MerR-like transcription activator , which senses cytoplasmic copper in the zeptomolar range ( Rae et al. 1999 ; Stoyanov et al. 2001 ; Outten et al. 2000 ; Petersen and Moller 2000 ; Changela et al. 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>CueR , a MerR-family transcription factor , stimulates copper-induced transcription of both copA encoding Cu ( I ) - translocating P-type ATPase pump ( exporter ) , that is the central component for maintenance of the copper homeostasis , and cueO encoding a periplasmic multicopper oxidase for detoxiﬁcation ( Outten et al. , 2000 ; Petersen and Moller , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regulation of the copper-responsive genes by CueR Another copper-responsive transcription factor CueR activates transcription of copA and cueO in the presence of copper ion ( Outten et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>When grown in the presence of copper , DcomC cells had higher periplasmic and cytoplasmic copper levels , compared to the wild-type , as assessed by the activation of the periplasmic CusRS sensor and the cytoplasmic CueR sensor , respectively .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under the aerobic experimental conditions herewith employed , CueR senses lower concentrations of copper than the CusSR system , and the induction levels of CueR-dependent copA and cueO after exposure to copper are higher than those of cusC and cusR , which are controlled by CusSR ( see Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>As cytoplasmic copper levels rise , the copA promoter , which is under the control of the E. coli CueR regulator , is induced and expression of the downstream lux genes results in luminescence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>As expected , this in turn also lead to increased cytoplasmic copper , as evident by the increased expression of copA , which is under the control of the cytoplasmic copper-sensing CueR regulator ( Fig. 6b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>To check that the response of CueR to gold was specific , a second member of this class of metal regulators , MerR and its promoter PmerTPAD , was tested in both E. coli TG1 and in E. coli CSH26 recA ( 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446701" target="_blank">12446701</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , it is not surprising that replacing alanine 78 with cysteine to mimic the equivalent essential cysteine in MerR ( Fig. 1 ) has no effect on CueR response to Hg ( II ) , as the spacing between Cys112 and Cys120 in CueR is different to that between Cys117 and Cys126 in MerR , and more subtle positioning and charge effects will undoubtedly be invovled in metal recognition .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446701" target="_blank">12446701</a>]<br></li>
<li>Half-maximal CueR induction occurs at a free Cu concentration of 2 10 21 1 10 21 M , corresponding to a zeptomolar CueR sensitivity for Cu ( Fig. 1B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12958362" target="_blank">12958362</a>]<br></li>
<li>ZntR responds to Cd as well as to Zn ( Brocklehurst II II et al. , 1999 ) , and CueR shows 37 % identity to ZntR across the length of the protein sequence ( Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11136469" target="_blank">11136469</a>]<br></li>
<li>The alterations ZntR ( H76A ) and ZntR ( H77A ) appeared to diminish ZntR-mediated Zn ( II ) induction to some extent but each shows a similar proﬁle to that for ZntR w.t. , this is surprising given the conservation seen between ZntR [ 10 ] , MerR [ 8 ] and CueR [ 25,26 ] in this region ( Fig. 5 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12445820" target="_blank">12445820</a>]<br></li>
<li>Multiple alignment of MerR [ 8 ] , ZntR [ 10 ] , CadR [ 27 ] , CueR [ 25,26 ] , and PbrR [ 28 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12445820" target="_blank">12445820</a>]<br></li>
