				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>The CueR box organized in the moa operon is located upstream of the ﬁrst gene , maoA , the CueR box centre being at 16-bp upstream of its translation initiation site ( Fig. 3B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>The CueR box is located upstream of the initiation codon of moaA but downstream of its transcription sites .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>The Escherichia coli Copper-responsive copA Promoter Is Activated by The copA gene of Escherichia coli encodes a copper transporter and its promoter is normally regulated by Cu ( I ) ions and CueR , a MerR-like transcriptional activator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446701" target="_blank">12446701</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcription of copA is regulated solely by CueR ( GeneBankTM AF318185 ) , a copper - and silver-responsive ( 7 , 8 , 10 ) member of the MerR family of transcriptional activators ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446701" target="_blank">12446701</a>]<br></li>
<li>As cytoplasmic copper levels rise , the copA promoter , which is under the control of the E. coli CueR regulator , is induced and expression of the downstream lux genes results in luminescence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>As expected , this in turn also lead to increased cytoplasmic copper , as evident by the increased expression of copA , which is under the control of the cytoplasmic copper-sensing CueR regulator ( Fig. 6b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22089859" target="_blank">22089859</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under the aerobic experimental conditions herewith employed , CueR senses lower concentrations of copper than the CusSR system , and the induction levels of CueR-dependent copA and cueO after exposure to copper are higher than those of cusC and cusR , which are controlled by CusSR ( see Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>The first system is cytoplasmatic and is mainly controlled by the Cu ( I ) metal sensor , CueR .8,9 CueR regulates the expression of two genes : copA , which encodes the Cu ( I ) - translocating P-type ATPase , and cueO , which encodes a Cu ( I ) - oxidizing multicopper oxidase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=25940871" target="_blank">25940871</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regulation of the copper-responsive genes by CueR Another copper-responsive transcription factor CueR activates transcription of copA and cueO in the presence of copper ion ( Outten et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>Among the known genes with the CueR box , copper-response transcription activation was observed for the moaABCDE operon , besides the copA and cueO genes ( see Table 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription regulation of the copA and cueO genes by CueR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15773991" target="_blank">15773991</a>]<br></li>
